{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-tsx","path":"/blog/creating-simple-vector-drawables-in-android-studio","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>Using vector drawables is often much better than bitmap images for two reasons: they scale without losing definition and you need only one asset file which fits all screen densities.</p>\n<p>Sometimes I find it useful to create vector drawables by hand in Android Studio using <a href=\"https://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/paths.html\">SVG paths</a>.</p>\n<p>If you are not yet familiar with it, let me show you an example.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/0f98f/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 66.89189189189189%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Image\"\n        title=\"Image\"\n        src=\"/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/1c72d/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/a80bd/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 148w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/1c91a/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 295w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/1c72d/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 590w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/a8a14/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 885w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/fbd2c/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 1180w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/0f98f/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image }</p>\n<h1>Example</h1>\n<p>I'm going to create a rectangle consisting of two adjacent triangles varying in color like below:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 350px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/585d0c17d01afe4215909bf16a3156db/13ae7/expected-rectangle-2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 100%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABQAAAAUCAYAAACNiR0NAAAACXBIWXMAABYlAAAWJQFJUiTwAAAAdElEQVQ4y63ROwqAMBAE0NxYiUT02IqFVpGkCCz57WeKYbvHDOu+c4+avEcgN+UJPjokdvlFDo6we1tl4AwTgRyMPZmLsRpKsCkoxYagBuuCWqwJWrAKtGIERGAFRGEZRGJVQytGGiIw8hQEVkAUlkEklsAfC2V5Ru+mNO0AAAAASUVORK5CYII='); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Rectangle\"\n        title=\"Rectangle\"\n        src=\"/static/585d0c17d01afe4215909bf16a3156db/13ae7/expected-rectangle-2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/585d0c17d01afe4215909bf16a3156db/12f09/expected-rectangle-2.png 148w,\n/static/585d0c17d01afe4215909bf16a3156db/e4a3f/expected-rectangle-2.png 295w,\n/static/585d0c17d01afe4215909bf16a3156db/13ae7/expected-rectangle-2.png 350w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image }</p>\n<h2>Step 1: Create a drawable file</h2>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/a8e3fb80f8d2fecaa07844c5d0608c82/da952/new_drawable.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.83783783783784%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"New drawable file\"\n        title=\"New drawable file\"\n        src=\"/static/a8e3fb80f8d2fecaa07844c5d0608c82/fcda8/new_drawable.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/a8e3fb80f8d2fecaa07844c5d0608c82/12f09/new_drawable.png 148w,\n/static/a8e3fb80f8d2fecaa07844c5d0608c82/e4a3f/new_drawable.png 295w,\n/static/a8e3fb80f8d2fecaa07844c5d0608c82/fcda8/new_drawable.png 590w,\n/static/a8e3fb80f8d2fecaa07844c5d0608c82/efc66/new_drawable.png 885w,\n/static/a8e3fb80f8d2fecaa07844c5d0608c82/c83ae/new_drawable.png 1180w,\n/static/a8e3fb80f8d2fecaa07844c5d0608c82/da952/new_drawable.png 1872w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image }</p>\n<h2>Step 2: Set up the drawable size</h2>\n<pre><code class=\"language-xml\">&#x3C;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?>\n&#x3C;vector xmlns:android=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"\n    android:height=\"100dp\"\n    android:width=\"100dp\"\n    android:viewportHeight=\"100\"\n    android:viewportWidth=\"100\">\n\n&#x3C;/vector>\n</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>android:width</code> and <code>android:height</code> properties define the drawable intrinsic size, so it matters mostly when you later use the drawable with <code>wrap_content</code> width and height like this:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-xml\">&#x3C;ImageView\n        android:src=\"@drawable/rectangle\"\n        android:layout_width=\"wrap_content\"\n        android:layout_height=\"wrap_content\" />\n</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>android:viewportWidth</code> and <code>android:viewportHeight</code> properties are more important for us as they define the canvas size for drawing our paths.</p>\n<h2>Step 3: Draw the first triangle</h2>\n<p>Let's fill a half of our squared canvas with the first triangle by drawing a path though its vertices: <strong>A</strong>, <strong>B</strong> and <strong>C</strong>.</p>\n<p>Please note the coordinates â€” the top-left corner of the canvas is (0,0) and the bottom-right corner is (100,100) and that's because we set the <code>android:viewportWidth=\"100\"</code> and <code>android:viewportHeight=\"100\"</code>.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/164d383491ba22b56f34114ae6230f5c/8c557/first_triangle.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 71.62162162162163%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"First triangle\"\n        title=\"First triangle\"\n        src=\"/static/164d383491ba22b56f34114ae6230f5c/fcda8/first_triangle.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/164d383491ba22b56f34114ae6230f5c/12f09/first_triangle.png 148w,\n/static/164d383491ba22b56f34114ae6230f5c/e4a3f/first_triangle.png 295w,\n/static/164d383491ba22b56f34114ae6230f5c/fcda8/first_triangle.png 590w,\n/static/164d383491ba22b56f34114ae6230f5c/8c557/first_triangle.png 700w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image }</p>\n<p>You can draw a path by adding a <code>path</code> inside the <code>vector</code>:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-xml\">&#x3C;path\n    android:fillColor=\"[your color (e.g. from resources or RGB Hex)]\"\n    android:pathData=\"[SVG path commands]\" />\n</code></pre>\n<p>We need the following SVG commands here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>M</strong>  â€” absolute <strong>moveto</strong></li>\n<li><strong>L</strong>  â€” absolute <strong>lineto</strong></li>\n<li><strong>z</strong>  â€” <strong>closepath</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Drawing the triangle consists of:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>starting a path from <strong>A=(0,0)</strong>: <code>M 0,0</code></li>\n<li>drawing a line to <strong>B=(100,0)</strong>: <code>L 100,0</code></li>\n<li>drawing a line to <strong>C=(0,100)</strong>: <code>L 0,100</code></li>\n<li>closing the path: <code>z</code></li>\n</ol>\n<p>We could also use the relative <strong>lineto (<code>l</code>)</strong> command instead and provide the vectors connecting the points like this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>from <strong>A</strong> to <strong>B</strong>: <code>l 100,0</code></li>\n<li>from <strong>B</strong> to <strong>C</strong>: <code>l -100,100</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>It's also worth noting that if you use the same command multiple times in a row, the command letter can be eliminated on subsequent commands. So the final command looks like this: <code>M 0,0 L 100,0 0,100 z</code></p>\n<p>Let's put this in the drawable file:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-xml\">&#x3C;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?>\n&#x3C;vector xmlns:android=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"\n    android:height=\"100dp\"\n    android:width=\"100dp\"\n    android:viewportHeight=\"100\"\n    android:viewportWidth=\"100\">\n\n    &#x3C;path\n        android:fillColor=\"@color/triangle_red_light\"\n        android:pathData=\"M 0,0 L 100,0 0,100 z\" />\n\n&#x3C;/vector>\n</code></pre>\n<p>We can see the triangle in the preview panel:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/b34d5b085d663ddc90021e41fc7598ec/f1f01/first_triangle_preview.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 40.54054054054054%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"First triangle preview\"\n        title=\"First triangle preview\"\n        src=\"/static/b34d5b085d663ddc90021e41fc7598ec/fcda8/first_triangle_preview.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/b34d5b085d663ddc90021e41fc7598ec/12f09/first_triangle_preview.png 148w,\n/static/b34d5b085d663ddc90021e41fc7598ec/e4a3f/first_triangle_preview.png 295w,\n/static/b34d5b085d663ddc90021e41fc7598ec/fcda8/first_triangle_preview.png 590w,\n/static/b34d5b085d663ddc90021e41fc7598ec/efc66/first_triangle_preview.png 885w,\n/static/b34d5b085d663ddc90021e41fc7598ec/c83ae/first_triangle_preview.png 1180w,\n/static/b34d5b085d663ddc90021e41fc7598ec/f1f01/first_triangle_preview.png 2212w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image }</p>\n<h2>Step 4: Draw the second triangle</h2>\n<p>As we already know how to draw a path, it's very simple to create another triangle. Its vertices are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>B=(100,0)</strong></li>\n<li><strong>C=(0,100)</strong></li>\n<li><strong>D=(100,100)</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>so the path command is: <code>M 100,0 L 0,100 100,100 z</code></p>\n<p>The resulting XML now looks like this:</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-xml\">&#x3C;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?>\n&#x3C;vector xmlns:android=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"\n    android:height=\"100dp\"\n    android:width=\"100dp\"\n    android:viewportHeight=\"100\"\n    android:viewportWidth=\"100\">\n\n    &#x3C;path\n        android:name=\"dark_triangle\"\n        android:fillColor=\"@color/triangle_red_dark\"\n        android:pathData=\"M 100,0 L 0,100 100,100 z\" />\n\n    &#x3C;path\n        android:name=\"light_triangle\"\n        android:fillColor=\"@color/triangle_red_light\"\n        android:pathData=\"M 0,0 L 100,0 0,100 z\" />\n\n&#x3C;/vector>\n</code></pre>\n<p>Hint: you can name the paths so it's easier to find them later if your drawable gets more complicated.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/1220b9d38026af81e545a1beb1c75636/8711f/second_triangle_preview.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 39.86486486486486%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Second triangle preview\"\n        title=\"Second triangle preview\"\n        src=\"/static/1220b9d38026af81e545a1beb1c75636/fcda8/second_triangle_preview.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/1220b9d38026af81e545a1beb1c75636/12f09/second_triangle_preview.png 148w,\n/static/1220b9d38026af81e545a1beb1c75636/e4a3f/second_triangle_preview.png 295w,\n/static/1220b9d38026af81e545a1beb1c75636/fcda8/second_triangle_preview.png 590w,\n/static/1220b9d38026af81e545a1beb1c75636/efc66/second_triangle_preview.png 885w,\n/static/1220b9d38026af81e545a1beb1c75636/c83ae/second_triangle_preview.png 1180w,\n/static/1220b9d38026af81e545a1beb1c75636/8711f/second_triangle_preview.png 2214w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image }</p>\n<h2>Step 5: Use the drawable with an ImageView</h2>\n<p>Now we can use the drawable. As you can see, it can be easily scaled by using the <code>android:layout_width</code>, <code>android:layout_height</code> and <code>android:scaleType</code> properties.</p>\n<pre><code class=\"language-xml\">&#x3C;?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"utf-8\"?>\n&#x3C;LinearLayout xmlns:android=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"\n    xmlns:app=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res-auto\"\n    android:orientation=\"vertical\"\n    android:layout_width=\"match_parent\"\n    android:layout_height=\"match_parent\">\n\n    &#x3C;ImageView\n        android:layout_width=\"match_parent\"\n        android:layout_height=\"match_parent\"\n        android:scaleType=\"fitXY\"\n        app:srcCompat=\"@drawable/rectangle\" />\n\n&#x3C;/LinearLayout>\n</code></pre>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/7547ea09323ffd502adc14fb8b1a73c5/8ad1b/layout.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 66.89189189189189%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Final layout\"\n        title=\"Final layout\"\n        src=\"/static/7547ea09323ffd502adc14fb8b1a73c5/fcda8/layout.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/7547ea09323ffd502adc14fb8b1a73c5/12f09/layout.png 148w,\n/static/7547ea09323ffd502adc14fb8b1a73c5/e4a3f/layout.png 295w,\n/static/7547ea09323ffd502adc14fb8b1a73c5/fcda8/layout.png 590w,\n/static/7547ea09323ffd502adc14fb8b1a73c5/efc66/layout.png 885w,\n/static/7547ea09323ffd502adc14fb8b1a73c5/c83ae/layout.png 1180w,\n/static/7547ea09323ffd502adc14fb8b1a73c5/8ad1b/layout.png 2320w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>{: .center-image }</p>\n<h3>Further reading</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/material/drawables.html#VectorDrawables\">https://developer.android.com/training/material/drawables.html#VectorDrawables</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/graphics/drawable/VectorDrawable.html\">https://developer.android.com/reference/android/graphics/drawable/VectorDrawable.html</a></li>\n</ul>","excerpt":"Using vector drawables is often much better than bitmap images for two reasons: they scale without losing definition and you need only oneâ€¦","frontmatter":{"slug":null,"title":"Creating simple vector drawables in Android Studio","description":null,"author":"azabost","tags":["Android"],"date":"2017-10-18T22:00:00.000Z","image":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"constrained","backgroundColor":"#f8f8f8","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/d5217/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg","srcSet":"/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/fa695/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 480w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/a0d3e/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 960w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/d5217/desk-office-pen-ruler.jpg 1920w","sizes":"(min-width: 1920px) 1920px, 100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/95a23/desk-office-pen-ruler.webp 480w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/5bdbe/desk-office-pen-ruler.webp 960w,\n/static/f7ad19a38135f362df51e9ce95eb3ab8/618ea/desk-office-pen-ruler.webp 1920w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"(min-width: 1920px) 1920px, 100vw"}]},"width":1920,"height":1279}}}},"timeToRead":5,"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/new-www/new-www/src/mdData/blog/2017-10-19-creating-simple-vector-drawables-in-android-studio.md"},"site":{"siteMetadata":{"siteUrl":"https://brightinventions.pl"}}},"pageContext":{"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/new-www/new-www/src/mdData/blog/2017-10-19-creating-simple-vector-drawables-in-android-studio.md"}},"staticQueryHashes":["2189233960","3181594896"]}